                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseTwo" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwo" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">
                        <h6>The Obsolescence tracker initiative has three main goals:</h6>
                        <ul>
                            <li>To address the increasing consumer demand for environmental information about laptop</li>
                            <li>To raise awareness and transparency by creating a consistent way for consumers to identify and compare the most sustainable laptops</li>
                            <li>To encourage and incentivise suppliers to reduce the environmental impact of their devices.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThree">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThree" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThree">
                        Why do companies use programmed obsolescence?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseThree" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThree" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">Programmed obsolescence was theorized by Bernard London in 1932 to boost an economic model that had run out of steam during the Great Depression. Economic growth is based on the stimulation of production and consumption. The more people consume, the more companies gain orders and invest to produce more, which theoretically increases employment and sales. VAT also relies on consumption, which leads the government to strongly encourage it in order to finance public spending. Our economic and social model is based on overconsumption, which must be constantly renewed. However, it is possible to imagine alternative economic models that do not rely on overproduction, as shown by some new or transitional businesses (rental, repair, reconditioning, sustainable manufacturers...).
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFour">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFour" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFour">
                        Which laptop models have been rated so far?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseFour" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFour" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">By end of 2022 about 180 devices have been rated , and the total number of assessed devices by Obsolescence tracker is continuously increasing in order to keep the pace of new portfolio entrants so that the current growing demand from consumers for more transparency continues to be met. The rated devices can be found on the  websites and shops of the participating laptop operators.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingFive">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseFive" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseFive">
                        What is the legal definition of programmed obsolescence? What are the sanctions?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseFive" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingFive" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">After a first unsuccessful legislative proposal in 2013, the offence of programmed obsolescence was introduced in the Energy Transition Law in 2015.  Programmed obsolescence is now defined and punished by articles L441-2 and L454-6 of the Consumer Code. The law aimed at reducing the environmental footprint of the digital, enacted in November 2021, came to make the offense more easily applicable by removing part of the definition ("to increase the replacement rate"), which unnecessarily complicated it. The current definition is therefore :
                        Programmed obsolescence is defined as all techniques, including software, by which the marketer of a product aims to deliberately reduce its lifespan.
                        This offence is punishable by two years imprisonment and a fine of â‚¬300,000. The amount of the fine may be increased, in proportion to the benefits derived from the breach, to 5% of the average annual turnover, calculated on the last three annual turnovers known at the date of the facts.
                        The law of energy transition for green growth aims to improve the design of products by sanctioning programmed obsolescence. To learn more, visit the dedicated page of the website of the Ministry of Ecological Transition.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingSix">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseSix" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseSix">
                        What are the social issues of planned obsolescence?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseSix" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingSix" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">Many consumers have already experienced programmed obsolescence. In addition to penalizing the purchasing power of consumers, who are forced to change their appliances to buy new ones, programmed obsolescence generates a feeling of frustration and alienation. Programmed obsolescence is also the indirect cause of very difficult working conditions for subcontractors, especially in so-called "developing" countries. Indeed, the reduction in the life span of goods is accompanied by a reduction in production costs that weighs on employees. The production of certain objects such as telephones also gives rise to a struggle for resources that fuels social violence. Finally, programmed obsolescence promotes unsustainable consumption behaviors and institutionalizes every day a disposable culture.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
