                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseEight" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseEight">
                        What does durability mean and how is this related to sustainability or ecological performance?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseEight" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingEight" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">One of the key reasons why consumers replace their laptop are defects or wear and tear, which prematurely shortens the viable lifetime of the device.  The more durable the device, the less likely it is to be discarded early, reducing the greenhouse gases associated with the manufacture of a new device and reducing e-waste.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingNine">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseNine" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseNine">
                        Does repairability relate to the repair cost of the laptop?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseNine" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingNine" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">When repairing a laptop, a technician will need to disassemble the device, replace the defective part, and then reassemble it. Therefore, the cost of labor represents a significant portion of the overall cost of repairing a laptop. The design of a laptop makes disassembly and reassembly tedious and not very quick, so this element of the cost will vary.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTen">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTen" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTen">
                        Does ending planned obsolescence jeopardize prosperity and jobs?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseTen" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTen" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">Fighting against programmed obsolescence implies a change of economic model. It is about consuming and producing less, better, more local and ecological. If the end of programmed obsolescence would lead to changes in terms of employment, it would create new opportunities in other sectors. The European Commission estimates that the development of the circular economy could generate 170,000 additional jobs by 2030.
                        Thanks to the circular, collaborative, social and solidarity economy, it is possible to envisage new types of jobs in repair, services, sustainable development, local agriculture and many other sectors. At the same time, we need to engage in a global reflection on lifestyles, the exchange of goods and services, design, work and voluntary simplicity.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
