                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingEleven">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseEleven" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseEleven">
                        Does the increase in the life span of products imply a decrease in purchasing power?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseEleven" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingEleven" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">No, the increase in the life span of products will not reduce the purchasing power of consumers, on the contrary!
                        Currently, modest households suffer a double penalty: poor quality goods and frequent renewal. Some people argue that low-end goods allow easier access to consumption, because they are cheaper. However, programmed obsolescence is antisocial: not only are products of lesser quality reserved for the poorest, but they have to buy them more often and therefore lose purchasing power in the long term.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingTwelve">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseTwelve" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseTwelve">
                        What does the term demountability mean? Isn't it already compulsory to ensure that devices can be dismantled?</button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseTwelve" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingTwelve" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">The demountability indicates that the laptop can be easily dismantled, for example: replace the battery, the screen or the motherboard, especially if you want more power or autonomy. Also a key of the keyboard if it is broken. Each component has a barcode that allows you to have the reference and the instructions to install it.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            <div class="accordion-item">
                <h2 class="accordion-header" id="headingThirteen">
                    <button class="accordion-button collapsed" type="button" data-bs-toggle="collapse" data-bs-target="#collapseThirteen" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseThirteen">
                        What are the different types of programmed obsolescence?
                    </button>
                </h2>
                <div id="collapseThirteen" class="accordion-collapse collapse" aria-labelledby="headingThirteen" data-bs-parent="#accordionExample">
                    <div class="accordion-body">Programmed obsolescence can take various forms, including mainly : technical obsolescence, also called functional or structural obsolescence: when the good no longer functions because of the limited life span of one of its essential and irremovable components; we also speak of indirect obsolescence when spare or replacement parts are made inaccessible or withdrawn from the market (for example, the glass of the coffee maker is no longer sold);
                        Aesthetic obsolescence, also called psychological or cultural obsolescence: by the "old-fashioned" effect, when the professional markets new products in a short period of time that are touted as more efficient in promotional campaigns (for example, a company already has new technological advances that it reserves for its next product that will be marketed only a few months later). Aesthetic obsolescence is more pernicious in the sense that it is mainly done through advertising and marketing and encourages people to renew products before they fail (but for example because they want a bigger screen, more fashionable clothes...).
                        Software obsolescence mainly concerns smartphones or laptop for example, but is increasing with the multiplication of connected objects. It covers several techniques: ; the limitation of the technical support duration compared to the real usage duration; or the incompatibility of format between old and new software version: the mandatory update which is too heavy and which makes the device slow down, causing dysfunctions and inciting to buy a product again.
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
